<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 https://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <!--
    Chapter 36 companion (When Quality Meets Reality — Part IX closer). Release quality at the smallest
    size that still teaches it. The chapter is CONFIG-centric: the release process itself is illustrative
    configuration — a semantic-versioning policy (release/SEMVER-POLICY.md), a Keep a Changelog file
    (release/CHANGELOG.md), a release workflow in ci/release.yml, and a release-gate shell in
    release/release-gate.sh — and none of those files is run by this build. What is runnable and
    unit-tested here is the load-bearing decision the chapter argues for: the release-READINESS gate, in
    org.acme.release.ReleaseReadiness, which asserts the chapter's release preconditions before a tag is
    cut — the version is a release and not a -SNAPSHOT (semver, key 60), the changelog carries an entry
    for it, every CI gate is green on the release commit, the artifact is signed/attested with an SBOM
    (Part VII, key 66), and the staged build passed its smoke test. That makes `mvn -Pquality verify` the
    local equivalent of the release gate the workflow wires: the same preconditions the YAML checks are
    decided here and unit-tested. The module is built on the JDK alone (zero runtime dependencies), so it
    dogfoods the book and builds fast and green; its own signals are machine-checked by the `quality`
    profile (Checkstyle + SpotBugs).

    SOURCE-PIN: Java 21 anchor (build openjdk@21 21.0.11; forward-check 25.0.3); JUnit 6.x BOM + AssertJ
    3.27.7 inherited from the aggregator. Semver is the contract from semver.org (MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH;
    MAJOR=breaking, MINOR=additive, PATCH=fix — key 60). The release-plugin / versions-plugin version
    literals named in the workflow and policy are NOT separately pinned by SOURCE-PIN (§4 pins one Maven
    row, "Apache Maven (+ enforcer, versions plugins) 3.9.16") — see
    09-flags/83_release_versioning_plugin_versions_unpinned.md. The GitHub Actions in ci/release.yml are
    hosted/SaaS, dated-at-use 2026-06 (SOURCE-PIN §5), flagged for digest pinning at adoption.
  -->
  <parent>
    <groupId>org.acme.storefront</groupId>
    <artifactId>companion-code</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  </parent>

  <artifactId>release-quality</artifactId>
  <name>Chapter 36 — When Quality Meets Reality (release-quality)</name>

  <dependencies>
    <!--
      JDK-only at runtime: the release-readiness gate is plain Java, and the release tools the chapter
      names (the signing/SBOM step, the changelog tooling, the canary controller) run in the release
      pipeline, not as runtime dependencies here. The test libraries are the only additions, and their
      versions are inherited from the companion-code aggregator's dependencyManagement — no version
      literal lives in this module.
    -->
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.junit.jupiter</groupId>
      <artifactId>junit-jupiter</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.assertj</groupId>
      <artifactId>assertj-core</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>

  <!--
    Static-analysis rule gates (Chapter 16), opt-in via `-Pquality` so the default build stays fast. The
    maven-checkstyle-plugin ships an OLD bundled engine; we override it to the pinned engine via a
    plugin-level dependency — the build plugin and the analyzer engine are separate versions. This module
    is a direct child of the companion-code root, which pins no quality profile of its own, so the profile
    is declared here (the same shape the peer modules 62/67/75 use) and reads the config under this
    module's own config/ dir, keeping the module self-contained. This profile IS the local equivalent of
    the static-and-security stage in ci/release.yml.
  -->
  <profiles>
    <profile>
      <id>quality</id>
      <build>
        <plugins>
          <plugin>
            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
            <artifactId>maven-checkstyle-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>3.6.0</version>
            <dependencies>
              <dependency>
                <groupId>com.puppycrawl.tools</groupId>
                <artifactId>checkstyle</artifactId>
                <version>10.26.1</version>
              </dependency>
            </dependencies>
            <configuration>
              <configLocation>config/checkstyle/checkstyle.xml</configLocation>
              <consoleOutput>true</consoleOutput>
              <failOnViolation>true</failOnViolation>
              <violationSeverity>error</violationSeverity>
              <includeTestSourceDirectory>true</includeTestSourceDirectory>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>checkstyle-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
          <!--
            SpotBugs: the bytecode vantage point (Chapter 16), complementary to Checkstyle's source view.
            This module's model types are immutable records and a sealed verdict, and the gate exposes no
            mutable state, so the representation-exposure detectors stay quiet without suppression. The
            exclude filter is kept (empty) so a future, genuinely-reviewed suppression has a home with a
            reason, rather than being added inline.
          -->
          <plugin>
            <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
            <artifactId>spotbugs-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>4.9.3.0</version>
            <configuration>
              <effort>Max</effort>
              <threshold>Medium</threshold>
              <includeTests>false</includeTests>
              <excludeFilterFile>config/spotbugs/spotbugs-exclude.xml</excludeFilterFile>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>spotbugs-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
        </plugins>
      </build>
    </profile>
  </profiles>
</project>
